Date: Not suppliedAfter the talk at UT Austin, I spent Saturday at the Turkey=
 City science=20
fiction writers' workshop at Bruce Sterling's place. Turkey City is a venerab=
le=20
science fiction workshop that has spawned many good writers and a lexicon of =

science fiction critical terms that is the de facto standard for understandin=
g=20
what works and what doesn't in a work of science fiction:     Squid on the Ma=
ntelpiece     Chekhov said that if there are dueling pistols over the mantelp=
iece in the=20
    first act, they should be fired in the third. In other words, a plot=20
    element should be deployed in a timely fashion and with proper dramatic=20
    emphasis. However, in SF plotting the MacGuffins are often so overwhelmin=
g=20
    that they cause conventional plot structures to collapse. It's hard to=20
    properly dramatize, say, the domestic effects of Dad's bank overdraft whe=
n=20
    a giant writhing kraken is levelling the city. This mismatch between the =

    conventional dramatic proprieties and SF's extreme, grotesque, or visiona=
ry=20
    thematics is known as the "squid on the mantelpiece."     Card Tricks in =
the Dark     Elaborately contrived plot which arrives at (a) the punchline of=
 a private=20
    joke no reader will get or (b) the display of some bit of learned trivia =

    relevant only to the author. This stunt may be intensely ingenious, and=20
    very gratifying to the author, but it serves no visible fictional purpose=
.=20
